 (10%)\\r\\n\\r\\nBegin the interview now with your introduction.\"},{\"role\":\"assistant\",\"content\":\"Hi! I\'m Sarah, and I\'ll be conducting your technical interview today for the PHP Developer position. To start, could you briefly introduce yourself and share what excites you most about this role?\"},{\"role\":\"user\",\"content\":\"Hi Sarah, thank you for the opportunity.\\r\\n\\r\\nMy name is Rinu, and I\\u2019m a PHP developer with a strong background in building web applications using Core PHP, MVC architecture, and MySQL, along with hands-on experience in WordPress development. Over the years, I\\u2019ve worked on developing and maintaining scalable applications, handling database design, business logic, and integrating user-facing features.\\r\\n\\r\\nWhat excites me most about the PHP Developer role is the chance to work more deeply on backend logic and problem-solving, rather than just surface-level implementations. I enjoy designing clean, maintainable code, improving performance, and turning complex requirements into reliable solutions. I\\u2019m particularly motivated by roles where I can continuously learn, take ownership of features, and contribute to building robust applications that add real value to users and the business.\"},{\"role\":\"assistant\",\"content\":\"Thanks for sharing that, Rinu! It sounds like you have a solid foundation in PHP and backend development.\\n\\nI see on your resume that you\\u2019ve worked with MVC architecture. Could you walk me through a specific project where you implemented MVC in PHP and explain how you structured the model, view, and controller layers?\"},{\"role\":\"user\",\"content\":\"One project where I implemented MVC architecture in PHP was a custom web application for managing users and roles.\\r\\n\\r\\nIn this project, I clearly separated responsibilities across the three layers:\\r\\n\\r\\nModel:\\r\\nThe model layer handled all database interactions. Each model was responsible for a specific entity, like UserModel or RoleModel. I used methods for CRUD operations, data validation, and business rules related to that entity. This helped keep database logic isolated and reusable.\\r\\n\\r\\nController:\\r\\nControllers acted as the bridge between the model and the view. They handled incoming requests, validated user input, called the appropriate model methods, and prepared data to be sent to the views. For example, the user controller managed actions like creating users, assigning roles, and handling authentication.\\r\\n\\r\\nView:\\r\\nThe view layer focused only on presentation. I used PHP templates to display data passed from the controller, keeping logic minimal\\u2014mainly loops and conditionals for rendering. This ensured the UI stayed clean and easy to maintain.\\r\\n\\r\\nThe most challenging part was deciding what logic belongs in the controller versus the model. I addressed this by keeping business rules and database logic strictly in the models, while the controllers handled request flow and coordination. This made the application easier to scale and debug over time.\"},{\"role\":\"assistant\",\"content\":\"That\\u2019s a great breakdown, Rinu! It sounds like you have a strong grasp of MVC separation of concerns.\\n\\nTo dig a little deeper\\u2014how did you handle dependencies between models in this project? For example, if a *User* needed to interact with a *Role*, did you instantiate one model inside another, or did you use a different approach?\"},{\"role\":\"user\",\"content\":\"Sorry\"},{\"role\":\"assistant\",\"content\":\"No worries at all! Let me rephrase the question to make it clearer.\\n\\nIn your MVC project, when a *User* needed to check or assign a *Role*, how did you manage that interaction between the two models? Did you directly create a new *RoleModel* inside the *UserModel*, or did you use something like dependency injection or a service layer to keep them separate?\"}]', 4, 3, 'completed', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL,