eries with proper indexing to reduce query time.\\r\\n\\r\\nUsed pagination for displaying large tables to avoid fetching all records at once.\\r\\n\\r\\nAdded input validation and sanitization to prevent SQL injection and ensure data integrity.\\r\\n\\r\\nThis experience strengthened my understanding of Core PHP, MVC principles, and database optimization, and it was rewarding to see the system perform smoothly even with heavy data usage.\"},{\"role\":\"assistant\",\"content\":\"That\\u2019s a great example, Rinu! It sounds like you handled some important performance considerations.\\n\\nBuilding on that, could you explain how you structured the code in this project to follow MVC principles? Specifically, how did you separate the business logic from the presentation layer?\"},{\"role\":\"user\",\"content\":\"No idea\"},{\"role\":\"assistant\",\"content\":\"No worries at all, Rinu! MVC can be a bit abstract when you\'re first getting started with it.\\n\\nLet me rephrase: In that customer management system, how did you organize your PHP files to keep the logic (like processing data) separate from the HTML or UI parts? For example, did you have separate folders for different types of code?\"}]', 4, 3, 'completed', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2026-01-23 12:00:19', '2026-01-23 12:01:47', NULL),
